metadata.name: Viral Refraction #2
metadata.description:
"Viral Refraction" is a mesmerizing generative art piece that offers a unique perspective on the ongoing pandemic. 

The close-up view of different variants of the COVID-19 virus is rendered in an abstract and dynamic composition, with the use of vibrant colors and intricate shapes to create a sense of movement and depth. 

This artwork highlights the unique characteristics of variants and evokes a sense of uncertainty and unpredictability that has become synonymous with the ongoing pandemic. 

This generative piece serves not only as a visual representation of the COVID-19 variants but also as a reflection on the challenges posed by the virus and its impact on the world. It's a conversation starter that is sure to leave a lasting impression on all who view it.

Disclaimer:
The use of the variant names in this artistic project are purely for the sake of creating a visual representation of the virus. This artwork is not meant to provide any scientific or factual information about viruses and should not be used for any medical or research purposes. The artist's interpretation of the virus is solely for creative expression and is not intended to reflect actual characteristics of the virus.

metadata.description:

metadata.name: SCHNEEWALD #89
metadata.description:
SCHNEEWALD is the second release in a row of about 12 tree/flower generative art works, which have come together over the last 10 years.

This project explores an approach to trees with snow using a recursive algorithm and includes Three traits: a density layer for the amount of trees and another layer for the amount snow and a third for how strong the branches bend.

Rendering progress indicated on the top left border
Press [s] in live view to download a high resolution png

Artist notes:
Since I moved to Wandlitz, north of Berlin, in the middle of the "Naturpark Barnim" (https://www.barnim-naturpark.de/), in 2003,
I've done a lot of exploring nearby nature. In addition to the beautiful lake and heath landscapes, I fell in love with the wild acacia forests. These strange trees, sometimes more like huge wild grasses, grow so wildly into each other.

I experienced it in all sorts of seasonal change, packed with snow is definitely among the most amazing! 

While playing around with different branching system code snippets, a more and more complex image composition came together. The final script for this project on fx(hash) was finally given more randomness for a wider range of different outputs and an additional random grain filter.

Project link: https://e-art.co/project/schneewald/

Many thanks to jesse (jbird) for the good collaboration, which ultimately made it possible to get this work released.

metadata.name: Utopian Skyline #77
metadata.description:
Continuing the exploration of linear composition in the previous work, this work shows the utopian urban structure in an abstract form by using diagonal and non-uniform lines. To make this artwork more scattered and visually dynamic, just like musical notes that have to be interrupted somewhere, the lines are scattered and discontinuous using an animation algorithm. To see the artwork in detail, open it in high quality and zoom in. Various densities and color palettes have been used.

-----------

- Add &density=2 to 12 to the live view URL to render the image at higher resolution.

- Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Automatic #385
metadata.description:
Cellular automata is fascinating :) Applications ranging from physics and biology to modeling and architecture, with artistic and aesthetic representation always following along. Perfect example for emergence, how simple even byte-size rules result in complex structures, forming patterns and unpredictable behaviors...

This one is simple, 1d elementary cellular automata and the 256 rules as the foundation, where each iteration consists of the following elements: base rules - 3 are selected and allocated into the start row compositions, a set of shapes is assigned to a grid of various sizes. Occasionally, dynamic rule set is added - where a rule is randomly transformed into another random rule on a random row of the grid. A vertical or horizontal alignment of the grid is chosen an a color set assigned. Sometimes, a simple 2d noise is applied to lighten (or well, darken) things a bit. The grid is finite and confined by the amount of cells in a row and amount of rows fitting the canvas given cell size.

The properties are recorded as features, more as a reference to the building blocks, rather then rarity indication. Probably be best viewed in live mode :)

Pressing 's' in live mode will save the png of the output.

metadata.name: This is the lie  #487
metadata.description:
The Project of the Nameless Sheep stems from an artistic and provocative necessity that aims to conceptually unite the Orwellian philosophy of 1984 with the thoughts of the great master Modigliani. The latter once stated, "I shall paint your eyes only when I know your soul."

The collection is a cry of disagreement towards destructive and uncontrollable globalization. It draws inspiration from an impersonal observation of modern society, critically examining historical events, corporations, and notable figures who have sold their soul for individualistic power that disregards the lives of others and the environment.

An ever-evolving project that will mature its search for soulless bodies over time.

1984 token, at a price as provocative as the theme of the collection.

Any reference to individuals, things or concepts is entirely coincidental and generated by a hash.

metadata.name: Scaffold #116
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: Nil #69
metadata.description:
A balanced combination of spatial subdivision and algorithm sonification. A subdivision surface algorithm is recursive in nature: the process starts with a base level of area, and a refinement scheme is then applied to this field. This process takes that element and subdivides it, creating new segmented areas. The positions of the new areas are computed based on the positions of nearby old fields, edges, and/or faces. A cellular automata is running on the texture of some of these areas, building continuous, tautological worlds of binary patterns and relationships. Thus, unfolding of a pixel’s ‘umwelt’ can be witnessed through the slow, contemplative process.

The audio synthesis consists of a stochastic melody that emerges along the division of the new areas and territories within the image structure. This melody is complemented with tiny micro sounds, triggered by each new generation of the surface mounted cellular automata. 

Touch to listen
